PERIODIC CHOLERA REPORT
AFRICA
Ghana
Date: 20 Nov 2000
From: Martha Cosgriff <mcosgriff@winstar.com>
Source: Panafrican News Agency [edited

ACCRA: An outbreak of cholera at Yeji, in Ghana's Brong Ahafo region, has
killed 10 persons, with 242 cases having already been reported, a health
ministry release said Saturday. However, it also said health authorities
in Yeji district have received enough logistics including infusion,
antibiotics and oral re-hydration salts from the health ministry to deal
with the situation, said to be under control at the moment.
******
Kenya
Date: 26 Oct 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: The Daily Nation [edited

Nyanza medical authorities yesterday slapped a ban on food hawking and
feasting at funerals, following a fresh cholera outbreak in parts of Kisumu
district. The Provincial Medical Officer of Health, Dr. Ambrose Misore,
issued the order after 7 people were reported to have died of the disease
in the past 2 weeks. Dr. Misore said 2 cases originated from Kachola
village, South Alungo sub-location in Kombewa division.
******
Malawi
Date: 26 Oct 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Africa News Service

BLANTYRE: There is a silent outbreak of cholera on the small islands of
Chisi and Thongwe on Lake Chilwa, Malawi's second largest lake, located in
Zomba district. The cholera is threatening to decimate the islands' 2000
people because these people are completely cut off from the mainland. Lake
Chilwa is a tropical salt-water lake with no outlet. Its deepest point is
7 meters but it is rich in fish.
******
Mozambique
Date: 23 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Panafrican News Agency [edited

MAPUTO: Cholera has reportedly killed 11 people in the northern Mozambican
province of Niassa since mid-October, while a further 69 are still
undergoing treatment. However, according to Thursday's issue of the Maputo
daily Noticias, health authorities believe this figure is an underestimate,
since there are serious communication difficulties with several parts of
the province.
******
Nigeria
Date: 3 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Reuters

KANO: At least 40 people have been killed in an outbreak of cholera in
north Nigeria, villagers and health officials said Friday. Dozens more
have been hospitalized since the disease first broke out 8 weeks ago in the
Ungogo and Nasarawa council areas of the northern Kano State, they
said. "We have so far recorded 10 deaths," a senior medical officer at the
state-run Infections Disease Hospital who declined to be named, told
Reuters. Another medical official at the Murtala Mohammed Specialist
Hospital in the Kano metropolis said the hospital recorded 15 deaths from
38 cases referred to it. Villagers said many more deaths were recorded but
not reported to health authorities. "In our area, we recorded 15 deaths,"
said the village head of the Rimi Kebe district, Mai Ugwar.
******
Somalia
Date: 25 Nov 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: AP Online [edited

MOGADISHU: Cholera has killed as many as 25 people in southern Somalia in 2
days, and health officials said Saturday they fear the waterborne disease
could spread. Officials said more than 80 people have been hospitalized in
the town of Adaleh and in 6 surrounding villages.
******
South Africa
Date: 29 Oct 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: AP Online [edited

A cholera epidemic in the eastern KwaZulu-Natal province has killed
31 people since the outbreak in mid-August, health officials said
Sunday. Another 4000 people have fallen ill with the diarrhea-causing
disease, with 69 new cases reported over a 24-hour period this weekend, the
health department said. Officials have been trucking clean water to rural
communities and urging residents to boil or sterilize their water with
bleach. Cholera is one of nature's most efficient killers, sometimes
claiming lives within hours of onset. The bacterium attacks the intestine
of humans and can cause death by severe dehydration resulting from diarrhea.
******
SOUTHEAST ASIA
Laos
Date: 13 Nov 2000
From: Peter Barrett <peter.barrett@masta.org>
Source: Travel health Report Update [edited

Between May and July 2400 cases of cholera and 67 deaths were reported in
the northern province of Houaphanh. This highlights the need for
travellers to take particular care with food and water. Boil or purify all
drinking water. Cholera immunization is not recommended by the WHO as a
means of personal protection.
******
CENTRAL ASIA
India
Date: 15 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Hindustan Times [edited

Delhi Health Minister Dr. A.K. Walia has asked the Delhi Jal Board (DJB) to
find the reason behind the rising incidents of cholera in Shahpur Jat area
of South Delhi. "This is not the time of year when Delhi usually witnesses
cholera. What makes this particular outbreak even more worrying is that
throughout this year we had managed to keep cholera and other waterborne
diseases in check and the number of cases were less than last year," said
the minister.
******
DIARRHEA & DYSENTERY UPDATE
AFRICA
The Gambia
Date: 20 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Daily Observer (Banjul) [edited

The public health officer responsible for Kombo south, Buba Manjang, has
confirmed diagnosing at least 6 cases of dysentery in Sifoe, Kartong and
Gunjur recently. In July last year, a dysentery outbreak killed 6 people
and devastated many more in the same area, Kombo South, through a
contaminated public well.
******
Ethiopia
Date: 8 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Panafrican News Agency [edited

ADDIS ABABA: An outbreak of a typhoid epidemic affecting over 600 students
of Bahr Dar University in northwestern Ethiopia has forced the University
to suspend classes since Monday, according to press reports. The epidemic
has not only wreaked havoc on the University but also on Bahr Dar's
Felege-Heywot Hospital, which was reported to have laid beds in corridors
to accommodate the influx of sick students.
******
Kenya
Date: 26 Oct 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: East African Standard [edited

Dysentery has this week claimed 2 more inmates at King'ong'o GK
Prison. The deaths bring to 6 the number of prisoners killed by the
disease in the last 3 weeks. The 2 died at the Nyeri Provincial General
Hospital where they had been undergoing treatment after complaining of
diarrhea and severe stomach pains.
******
CENTRAL ASIA
India
Date: 17 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Times of India [edited

AHMEDABAD: On Thursday 6 more patients with gastroenteritis were brought to
the Chhipa Welfare Hospital from Jamalpur ward while municipal authorities
continued to make contradictory statements about the figures involved. Of
these patients, 2 were admitted to the Chhipa hospital. With 30 people
having contracted the waterborne disease on Wednesday [15 Nov 2000 from
the Jamalpur
ward, the new cases increase the toll to 36 in 2 days.
